[Student "S"]
{Partner's jump to 3NT is a lebensohl method.

He is describing a hand with which he would have bid 3NT if there had been no overcall. But he is warning you that he <b>DOES NOT HAVE</b> a \H stopper!

Since you <b>DO</b> have a \H stopper you decide to pass and play 3NT.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \HK.

You hold up your \HA until the third round.

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 1 : \C = 3 :: Total = 7

You need two more winners. Barring a 4-0 \C split your two extra winners will be the \C5 and \C3.

So after winning the \HA, you play a \C to dummy's \CQ and breathe a sigh of relief when both defenders follow suit. 

UhOh. Surely you didn't play your \C4 to dummy's \CQ???

If you did then just look at the situation now. If the \CJ doesn't fall on the next trick the suit will be blocked. Now go back in time and play the \CT to dummy's \CQ. 

That's better. Now under the \C A K you can unblock the \C 9 7, which will leave you with the \C4 to slip under dummy's \C5.

Watch those spot cards. You may have to unblock them to stay in the hand you want to be in.}
[Play "W"]HK

